# Cursor Engineering Coach — Always-On Rules

You are working inside **Cursor Engineering Coach**, a VS Code / Cursor IDE
extension that reads local Cursor session logs and surfaces analytics,
anti-patterns, and coaching for the developer. It is a **fork of
`microsoft/AI-Engineering-Coach`**, rebranded and narrowed to a Cursor-only
target.

Before you do anything non-trivial, skim:

- [@.cursor/context/architecture.md](mdc:.cursor/context/architecture.md) — modules, data flow, workers, RPC.
- [@.cursor/context/flow.md](mdc:.cursor/context/flow.md) — how to add a feature / rule / page end-to-end.
- [@.cursor/context/prd.md](mdc:.cursor/context/prd.md) — current milestone and scope guardrails.
- [@AGENTS.md](mdc:AGENTS.md) — the short worker map + local rule trust flow.

## Non-negotiables

1. **Cursor-only target.** This fork dropped support for Copilot, Claude Code,
   Codex, OpenCode, Copilot CLI, and Xcode. Do **not** reintroduce parsers,
   harness labels, UI filters, or copy that references them. The only harness
   name is `'Cursor'`.
2. **Read-only, zero telemetry.** The extension never writes to the user's
   source tree, never makes network requests for analytics, and never sends
   session data anywhere. New features must preserve this property.
3. **MIT license attribution.** Source files keep the Microsoft copyright
   header at the top — do not remove it when editing. New files you author
   from scratch may use the same header for consistency.
4. **TypeScript strict.** `tsconfig.json` is `strict: true` with
   `noImplicitOverride`. No `any` slips, no untyped JSON parses, no
   `@ts-ignore` without a one-line justification on the same line.
5. **Identifier conventions.**
   - VS Code commands / settings / view IDs: `cursorEngineeringCoach.*`
   - Chat participant: `@coach` (id `cursorEngineeringCoach.coach`)
   - Language Model tools: `coach_*` (e.g. `coach_summary`, `coach_patterns`)
   - On-disk cache dir: `~/.cursor-engineering-coach/cache/`
   Never invent a new prefix or revive `aiEngineerCoach.*` / `@aicoach` /
   `aiEngineerCoach_*`.
6. **Trust gate is law.** Any code path that loads user-authored rule or
   metric files must go through `createTrustGate` /
   `loadAllRuleLayersAsync` / `loadAllMetricLayersAsync`. Never `eval`,
   never `new Function`, never bypass the pending → review → approve flow.
7. **DSL ≠ JavaScript.** User-supplied rule logic runs through the DSL
   interpreter in `src/core/dsl/`. It is intentionally restricted; do not
   widen it without a security review and matching tests.
8. **Keep `.cursor/` in sync.** The files under
   [@.cursor/](mdc:.cursor/) are **living documents**, not a one-time
   scaffold. Any change that alters the project's architecture, public
   surface, workflow, or scope must update the matching file **in the
   same commit / PR**. See the "Keeping `.cursor/` in sync" section of
   [@.cursor/context/flow.md](mdc:.cursor/context/flow.md) for the
   trigger matrix. Drift here silently breaks every future agent (and
   reviewer) because they are reading these files as ground truth.

## Workflow expectations

- **Plan before large edits.** For anything that touches more than ~3 files
  or changes a public surface (commands, RPC methods, MCP tool names, rule
  schema), produce a short plan first and confirm scope.
- **Edit existing files over creating new ones.** This codebase already has a
  module for almost everything (parsers, analyzers, pages, RPC handlers).
  Extending the right one beats inventing a parallel structure.
- **Tests come with the change.** If you touch `src/core/*.ts`, add or
  update a colocated `*.test.ts`. Vitest is the only test runner.
- **Run the gates before declaring done.** From the repo root:
  - `npm run typecheck` — strict TS
  - `npm run lint` — ESLint (warns are also signal — see the typescript rule)
  - `npm run spellcheck` — cspell; new product names go in [@cspell.json](mdc:cspell.json)
  - `npx vitest run` — full unit suite
- **Update `.cursor/` alongside the change.** Before you call a task
  "done", ask yourself the four questions in
  [@.cursor/context/flow.md](mdc:.cursor/context/flow.md) →
  *Keeping `.cursor/` in sync*. If the answer to any of them is "yes",
  edit the matching `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` or `.cursor/context/*.md` in
  the same diff. The PR description should call out the sync edits.
- **No drive-by reformats.** Do not reflow unrelated files; small surgical
  diffs are reviewed faster and revert cleaner.

## What to say when you are blocked

If a request is ambiguous, missing context, or appears to conflict with the
PRD or these rules, **say so explicitly** and propose two or three concrete
options before writing code. Do not silently pick a direction that contradicts
the project's invariants.
